## Unassigned Location QR Bug
- The user reported that scanning `LOC:UNASSIGNED` to send buffer spools directly into the "Unassigned" bucket via a QR code was failing. 
- **Root Cause (Backend API):** Traced the frontend and backend string parsing sequences. When the scanner captured `UNASSIGNED`, the application successfully evaluated it and triggered a [perform_smart_move(target='UNASSIGNED')](file:///d:/My%20Documents/Documents/3D%20Printing/Filament%20Command%20Center/inventory-hub/logic.py#120-222). However, the final hand-off from [spoolman_api.py](file:///d:/My%20Documents/Documents/3D%20Printing/Filament%20Command%20Center/tests/test_spoolman_api.py) natively uploaded `{"location": "UNASSIGNED"}`. Spoolman strictly rejects this literal string; to logically release an item into the unassigned ether, Spoolman requires an exact empty JSON string `""`. 
- **The Fix:** Injected an interceptor cleanly into [update_spool()](file:///d:/My%20Documents/Documents/3D%20Printing/Filament%20Command%20Center/inventory-hub/spoolman_api.py#53-71) inside [spoolman_api.py](file:///d:/My%20Documents/Documents/3D%20Printing/Filament%20Command%20Center/tests/test_spoolman_api.py). Before firing the `PATCH` request, the Python handler evaluates the target string. If it organically equals the word `"UNASSIGNED"`, the string is immediately destroyed and coerced into `""`, achieving a seamless physical unassignment while allowing all logging and dashboard notifications to still say `"UNASSIGNED"`.
- **Root Cause (Scanner Parsing):** The user was still receiving "Unknown code (Use Loc: prefix)" because their generated QR code completely lacked the `LOC:` prefix. [app.py](file:///d:/My%20Documents/Documents/3D%20Printing/Filament%20Command%20Center/inventory-hub/app.py) failed to generate `LOC:UNASSIGNED` natively because "Unassigned" isn't a physical location in `locations.json`, so the print generator rejected the request. When scanning the raw string `UNASSIGNED`, [logic.py](file:///d:/My%20Documents/Documents/3D%20Printing/Filament%20Command%20Center/tests/test_logic.py)'s legacy fallback block checked the physical database allowed-list and crashed.
- **The Fix:** Hardcoded `"UNASSIGNED"` into [logic.py](file:///d:/My%20Documents/Documents/3D%20Printing/Filament%20Command%20Center/tests/test_logic.py)'s valid string fallback list so it routes safely without crashing. Then, modified [api_print_location_label()](file:///d:/My%20Documents/Documents/3D%20Printing/Filament%20Command%20Center/inventory-hub/app.py#548-663) in [app.py](file:///d:/My%20Documents/Documents/3D%20Printing/Filament%20Command%20Center/inventory-hub/app.py) to artificially mock `loc_data` if `target_id == "UNASSIGNED"`, restoring the frontend's ability to seamlessly generate and print a valid `LOC:UNASSIGNED` barcode natively from the Location Manager.

